Part I - PISA2012 Dataset Exploration¶

by HAMZAT ABDULRAHMAN¶

Introduction¶

The PISA - Programme for International Student Assessment - 2012 Data is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. The survey examines one: how well students have learned the school curriculum; two: how well prepared they are for life beyond school.\ About 490,000 15-year-old students in 65 economies contained in this dataset took part in the PISA2012 assessment of reading,mathematics, and science. The assessment is a measure of their ability to use these knowledge and skills to meet real life challenges. Of those economies, 44 economies took part in an assessment of creative problem solving, and 18 economies took part in an assessment of financial literacy. The dataset contains a wealth of information on students' background, their school and the organisation of education system.

# An attempt to drop NaN using .drop() left me with no single row in the dataframe

Quality Issue : Some ordinal variables are not of category data type¶

Define:¶

Create a function to convert the ordinal columns of interest to categorical data type, in order to minimize repetitve coding.

Code¶

In [134]:
# a function to convert a column to category datatype
def categorize(column_name,column_class):
    """A private function convert the input column of an already defined
     dataframe into a category datatype.
    It's first argument should be the column name,its second argument
    should be a variable that's already assigned an array - this array
    should have been arranged in its right order.
    
    e.g. categorize('cat_var','cat_class')"""
    
    classes = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True,categories=column_class)
    pisa_clean_df[column_name] = pisa_clean_df[column_name].astype(classes);
In [135]:
# create an array for the order of values
classes_1 = ['Strongly disagree','Disagree','Agree','Strongly agree']
classes_2 = ['Not at all likely','Slightly likely','Likely','Very   Likely']
classes_3 = ['Not at all like me','Not much like me','Somewhat like me','Very much like me','Mostly like me']
# call function to make conversion
categorize('ST29Q01',classes_1)
categorize('ST44Q05',classes_2)
categorize('ST94Q14',classes_3)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 485,490 students in this dataset, and it has 636 columns - most of which are qualitative in nature. The numerous columns are an exhaustive assessment of each student,and can be broadly categorised into three:

  1. Data on students' background,school and education system.
  2. Assessment data of students' skills and knowledge in mathematics,science and reading.
  3. Assessment data of students capability to tackle real life challenges after school.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in finding the factors that affect or are directly related to the performance of pupils in Mathematics asessment.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

"Gender" (ST04Q01); "Out-of-School Study Time" (OUTHOURS); "Interest in Mathematics" (ST29Q01);"Possession - textbooks"(ST26Q10), and lastly "Attribution to failure - Material too hard" (ST44Q05).

Since the data set has a lot of Qualitative variables, in order to minimize code repetiton, I'll be creating a function below to plot a barchart and its axis label for univariate analysis of Qualitative variables.

In [139]:
# a function to simply generate a barchart plot, for all qualitative variable in the  cleaned dataframe 
def barchart(x,label_name,long=False):
    
    """This barchart() function simply generates a seaborn.countplot() function,
    and customize the specified axis label with a plt.xlabel() or plt.ylabel() function call.
    
    The first argument is the name of the column to be plotted ,
    The second argument is the x_label or y_label,
    By default long = False, set long to true if you want the qualitative column
    on the y-axis instead. 
    e.g. barchart('column_name','x_or_ylabel',long=True)"""
    

    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    if (long==True):
        sb.countplot(data=pisa_clean_df,y=x,color=base_color);
        plt.ylabel(label_name);
        
    else:
        sb.countplot(data=pisa_clean_df,x=x,color=base_color);
        plt.xlabel(label_name);

Question 5:¶

Distribution of students' "out of school study hours" ?

Visualization¶

In [143]:
# plot histogram distribution of 'out-of-school study time'
bin_edges = np.arange(0,180+5,5)
sb.displot(pisa_clean_df['OUTHOURS'], bins=bin_edges);
plt.xlabel('Out-of-School Study Time (Hours)');

The above distribution is rightly skewed, so I thought of performing a log transformation. However,a log transformation cannot be applied directly because of '0' values in the data.\ Since a '0.001' hour is as good as '0.0' hour, I replaced all '0.0' in the column to '0.001'. Now a log transformation is possible because zeroes have been eliminated.

In [144]:
# replace 0 hours with 0.001 in the OUTHOURS column
pisa_clean_df['OUTHOURS'] = pisa_clean_df['OUTHOURS'].replace([0.0],0.001)
# set x-ticks
ticks = [0.001,0.1,0.3,1,3,10,30,100]
# set bin edges, and create plot
bin_edges = 10**np.arange(-3,2.26 + 0.25,0.25)
sb.displot(pisa_clean_df['OUTHOURS'], bins=bin_edges);
plt.xlabel('Out-of-School Study Time (Hours)');
# apply scaling and log transformation
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks(ticks,ticks);
plt.title("Log distribution of Out-of-School Study Time (Hours)");

Observation:¶

The log transformation distribution clearly shows that infact the zero hours are outliers.\ Students who study outside school between 5-10 hours had the highest count (above 35,000)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of my variable of interest - 'PV1MATH' (Perfomance Value in Mathematics) - is normal. No unsual points were detected and no outliers were seen. I did not need to perform any transformations since it is normal distributed.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The "OUTHOURS" column (Out-of-School Study Hours) had a right-skewed distribution. To apply a log transformation directly is impossible because it contains zero values of hour. I adjust the '0.0' hour values to '0.001', since 0.001 is as good as 0.0 .\ The elimination of zeroes allowed me to make a scaling and log transformation. Aside this feature, no unusual distribution was observed for the other features I investigated.\ At the cleaning phase,I had dropped all null values present in the columns I investigated, so that I have less missing values. I also changed the ordinal variables to a categorical datatype for easy ordering when a plot is to be created.

Observation:¶

Though most pupils keep their study time between 0-50 hours,very few pupils try to study beyond that time. Log transformation cannot be applied, the column contains zero values of hours.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The male gender is more for those whose performance score is above 700 in Mathematics, than the female gender.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I was expecting a significant increase in study time for those who "strongly agree" to reading mathematics,who also perceived the material to be not-at-all-likely hard. Suprisingly, the distribution generally looks similar in shape for all.

Conclusions¶

Results :¶

The following are summaries of what I observed across the univariate,bivariate and multivariate explorations perfomed:

  1. Those who are in possession of textbooks have a higher mean performance score in Mathematics than those who don't have.
  2. The lower the degree of likeliness that the reading material is hard, the higher the mean performance score in Mathematics.
  3. Pupils from OECD countries performed quite better in Mathematics than their counterparts from Non-OECD countries.
  4. Even though more Females than males agreed to "Interest in Mathematics - Reading", and also more females than males do not perceive the material to be too hard,the male genders have a slightly higher Mathematics performance mean score than the females.\ A deeper look in the multivariate relationship shows that, this could be due to the fact that there are more males than females - of those who scored above 700 in mathematics performance.
  5. Most of those who scored higher than 700 in Mathematics opined that a likeness for complex problem solving is "somewhat" - "mostly" like them.

Limitations :¶

  1. I couldn't show strong correlations because most of the numerous columns in this dataset are categorical in nature.
  2. The dataset is greatly based on questionnaire, there could be human errors while answering: some pupils could perceive a wrong notion of themselves,while a work-it-out mathematical question would prove them wrong.
